<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n34007g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n34" href="#n34007g">N34 (VI.B.27)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n34all.htm#n34007g"> 7(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> berat</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">1. <i>The Patriarchate of Constantinople</i> or <i>New Rome</i>. &hellip; On the death or deposition of the patriarch, the Holy Synod and the National Mixed Council at once meet and elect a temporary substitute for the patriarch. Forty days afterwards the electoral assembly meets, under his presidency, and proceeds to make a list of twenty candidates (at the present day they must be metropolitans) &hellip;. This list is sent to the sultan, who has by prescription the right to strike out five names. From the fifteen which remain the electoral assembly chooses three. These names are then submitted to the clerical members of the assembly, <i>i.e.</i> to the member of the Holy Synod <font color="green">[and such metropolitans as happen to be in Constantinople at the time for some canonical reason]</font>, who meet in church, and, after the usual service, make the final selection. The patriarch-elect is presented to the Porte, which thereupon grants the <mark>berat</mark> or diploma of investiture and several customary presents; after which the new ruler is enthroned. <small> &ldquo;ORTHODOX EASTERN CHURCH&rdquo; <a name="EBOEC" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBOEC"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 337 [The Four Ancient Patriarchates]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
